Creativity, heritage, and immersive experiences are central to life at Mamula Island which is why we’re so excited about Artist in Residence project we started in collaboration with Balkan…Projects.
The journey begins with a week-long residency in which artists Ana Prvački, Irena Haiduk, Angelo Plessas and Milica Jankovic will explore Mamula Island and its surroundings, conduct workshops and engage in talks with locals. 
Following their visit, each artist will return to Mamula Island later in the summer to assemble a modular exhibition that takes guests on a sensory journey of contemplation and meditation.
Stay tuned for further updates, events, and opportunities to engage with the artists and their thought-provoking works. Or book a stay to see this artistic journey for yourself.

It’s so exciting sharing my new commission “The Mandala System” a project with @balkanprojects at @mamulaisland hotel. Thank you so much @marakaran and @balkanprojects curator @kleacharitou with @danai_giannoglou for inviting me to this beautiful experience both during the residency and the inauguration. Every day is great here!

This quilt is an ode to the interconnected journey🚀of humans with natural elements such as the sea 🌊 On the quilt I made traditional symbols of the tamata, these votive offerings 🦵 used for healing 👁️‍🗨️purposes that are found in icons in Balkan churches ⛪️ A wide variety of images adorn the quilt, such as sea waves 🌊 boats 🛥️ 🙌 coat of arms, ufo 🛸 and stars 🌟 but also cybernetic symbols volume 📶that are rooted in ancient 📜iconography. All symbols ☮️compose a collage including the architectural elements of the hotel which are circular and mandala-like when the hotel is seen from Google Maps. 

This is the first series of quilts that are inspired by board games that can be found in different spiritual retreats 🧘‍♀️that are played between people for deeper spiritual growth. So the quilt apart from its symbolic meaning can also become a device of consciousness, healing, and protection. ☯️🔆
